    <p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p>
            <term>Linear search</term> algorithms check each element in order
            until the desired value is found or all elements in the array or
            <c>ArrayList</c> have been checked. Linear search algorithms can
            begin the search process from either end of the array or
            <c>ArrayList</c>.
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <p>
            <term>Binary search</term> algorithms can only be used on data that
            has been <term>sorted</term> or stored in order. It checks the
            middle of the data to see if that middle value is less than, equal,
            or greater than the desired value and then based on the results of
            that it narrows the search. It cuts the search space in half each
            time.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </p>

    <p>
      If binary search requires the values in an array or list to be sorted, how
      can you do that? There are many sorting algorithms which are covered in
      the next lesson.
    </p>



    <p>
      Here is a version of the recursive binary search that works with an
      <c>ArrayList</c>. Click on CodeLens to step through the code.
    </p>

    <activity label="recursiveBinarySearchArrayList">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Here is a version of the recursive binary search that works with an
          ArrayList. Run the code below. Try searching for the value 3 and then
          the value 2 which is not in the ArrayList. What happens?
        </p>
      </statement>

      <program interactive="activecode">
        <![CDATA[
        import java.util.ArrayList;

        public class RecursiveBinarySearchArrayList
        {
            public static int recursiveBinarySearch(
                ArrayList<Integer> list, int start, int end, int target)
            {
                int middle = (start + end) / 2;
                // base case: check middle element
                if (target == list.get(middle))
                {
                    return middle;
                }
                // base case: check if we've run out of elements
                if (end < start)
                {
                    return -1; // not found
                }
                // recursive call: search start to middle
                if (target < list.get(middle))
                {
                    return recursiveBinarySearch(list, start, middle - 1, target);
                }
                // recursive call: search middle to end
                if (target > list.get(middle))
                {
                    return recursiveBinarySearch(list, middle + 1, end, target);
                }
                return -1;
            }

            public static void main(String[] args)
            {
                ArrayList<Integer> list = new ArrayList<>();
                list.add(3);
                list.add(7);
                list.add(12);
                list.add(19);
                list.add(22);
                list.add(25);
                list.add(29);
                list.add(30);
                int target = 25;
                int foundIndex = recursiveBinarySearch(list, 0, list.size() - 1, target);
                System.out.println(target + " was found at index " + foundIndex);
            }
        }
        ]]>
      </program>

    </activity>
